In article <x5u3huuc5q.fsf_-_@world.std.com>, bzs@world.std.com (Barry
Shein) wrote:
>I guess what I've always wondered is why the 9-track technology just
>keeled over and died. It would've seemed that all that magnetic
>real-estate just needed to have the kind of density technology that
>was being used on 8mm and DAT applied and it should have been very
>competitive, expensive, but tens and then hundreds of gigabytes per
>reel (again, just judging by the number of square inches of magnetic
>material in a typical "round" tape.)
>
>But to my knowledge no one really ever showed a 9-track beyond
>6250bpi, which was about 150MB on a standard 2400ft reel.
