Yes -- wouldn't it be fun to have the current high-end DLT tape technology
(70Gb on a CompacTape IV, which is not all that long, comparatively with
9-tracks), writing on a 2400' full-size magtape reel?  The mind boggles
with the thought of how many hundreds of gigs could be put there.  I would
also hope that with modern servo technology, designers could do away with
the extremely long tape paths (with vacuum columns and the like) that cause
much of the aerodynamic pain of moving the tape quickly. Since DLT format
writes fixed-sized, addressable blocks on the tape using a folded
multitrack scheme, an open-reel drive using that format would really be a
great-great-great-grandkid of DECtape!


The mind truly boggles...

